BRIEF DESCRIPTION OF THIS PACKAGE

The above files include a suite of lisp functions for working with
finite posets (poset = order = partially ordered set).

Included are functions to return the pasts and futures of individual 
elements and of sets of elements; to transitively close a
preorder (= acyclic relation) or a general relation; to pass from the
poset relation `<' to its set of ``links'' (link = minimal relation,
sometimes called ``covering relation''); to find the maximal and
minimal layers of a poset and the levels of its individual elements
(counting from the bottom); to compute the numbers of chains, paths
(path=saturated chain), spanning trees and spanning hasse-trees of a
poset.  From these last invariants, various fractal dimensions can be
computed, e.g.  the Myrheim-Meyer dimension.

Also present are several lisp functions and macros of general utility,
some serving as auxiliaries for the poset functions, and some being
useful in their own right.  Among them are macros designed to extend or
simplify lisp syntax and macros designed to cope with the lack of local
variables (mainly affecting emacs-lisp); examples of their use can be
seen in the source code.

All the functions and macros in this suite are designed to work equally
well with Emacs Lisp (elisp) and with true Common Lisp (TCL).  However,
most testing of them has been done with elisp.  Since the functioning of
elisp is quite consistent from machine to machine, if you have a working
emacs (of sufficiently high version number), you should be able to use
this package.  (I'm using use the word `package' in its informal
English sense, these libraries are not designed as a package in the
technical TCL sense.)


DOCUMENTATION

A large amount of documentation is contained within, and together with,
the functions themselves.  See in particular the listings at the
beginnings of the "bibliotek" files and the documentation strings
incorporated into the function definitions.  (The latter can be accessed
conveniently using the emacs command `describe-function')

There is also some general -- but still partly out of date -- documentation
in the file `Some.more.documentation' in this directory.   I hope to add
to it from time to time.


INSTALLATION

To get started, make a sub-directory of your home directory named "lisp"
and put in it all the files listed above.  (Some are here in .gz form,
and need to be decompressed.)

Then start up an emacs and load (or evaluate the contents of) the file
"preparations.el", after temporarily uncommenting the line
"(setq recompile t)" 
near the top of the file.  This should create byte-compiled versions
of the library files with names like "bibliotek.poset.elc".

Thereafter, just load the file "preparations.el" whenever you want to
use the package.

The installation procedure for gnu common lisp is similar, using the
file preparations.gcl instead of preparations.el.

